<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Acidity to Pizza Sauce Acidity</strong> - The tomato sauce's natural acidity (pH 4.3-4.9) requires wines with comparable or higher acidity to avoid tasting flat. Sangiovese-based wines like Chianti Classico (with malic and tartaric acid levels around 6-7 g/L) create perfect harmony, while low-acid wines like over-oaked Chardonnay will taste flabby against pizza's bright tomato notes.</li>

  <li><strong>Tannin Structure Must Balance Cheese Fat Content</strong> - Pizza's melted mozzarella contains 20-25% fat that coats the palate. Medium-tannin wines like Barbera d'Asti or Côtes du Rhône provide enough astringency to cut through the cheese without overpowering the dish. Avoid high-tannin wines like young Barolo, which will taste harsh against the creamy dairy proteins.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Red Wines Slightly Chilled at 60-62°F</strong> - Pizza's hot temperature and casual dining setting call for refreshing wines. Chill light to medium-bodied reds like Dolcetto or Frappato for 30 minutes in the refrigerator before serving. This temperature enhances their fruit flavors and makes them more food-friendly with warm, cheesy pizza.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Pizza Pairings</strong> - Pizza dining is immediate and informal—wines should be ready to drink upon opening. Choose wines that don't require aeration: young Primitivo, Barbera, or Montepulciano d'Abruzzo. If you must open an older wine, use a Venturi aerator for quick oxygenation rather than traditional decanting.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Larger Bowl Glasses for Aromatic Concentration</strong> - Pizza's competing aromas (garlic, herbs, melted cheese) require wines with pronounced aromatics. Pour Sangiovese or Nero d'Avola into Burgundy-style glasses with wider bowls to concentrate their cherry and herb notes, helping them compete with pizza's intense flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose 2-5 Year Old Wines for Optimal Balance</strong> - Pizza pairs best with wines in their primary fruit phase before secondary development. A 3-year-old Chianti Rufina offers fresh cherry and herb notes that complement pizza perfectly, while a 10-year-old bottle with dominant leather and earth notes can overwhelm the dish's straightforward flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Open Wine 15 Minutes Before Pizza Arrives</strong> - Hot pizza waits for no one, so have your wine ready. Open bottles just before the pizza is served to capture peak freshness—the bright acidity and fruit-forward character that makes Vermentino or young Sangiovese perfect pizza partners diminishes if left open too long.</li>

  <li><strong>Match Wine Intensity to Topping Complexity</strong> - Simple Margherita pizza pairs with delicate Pinot Grigio or light Dolcetto, while meat lovers' pizza demands robust wines like Primitivo or Aglianico. The wine's flavor intensity should echo the pizza's—delicate wines disappear against bold toppings, while powerful wines overwhelm simple preparations.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with thin-crust versus deep-dish pizza?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Thin-crust pizza pairs beautifully with lighter wines like Pinot Noir or Chianti Classico because the crispy base doesn't compete with delicate wine flavors. Deep-dish pizza's thick, doughy crust and heavier sauce load require more robust wines like Zinfandel or Barbera d'Alba to cut through the richness. The increased bread-to-topping ratio in deep-dish also calls for wines with higher acidity to cleanse the palate between bites.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine chilled or at room temperature with pizza?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red wines like Chianti or Sangiovese should be served slightly cooler than room temperature (60-65°F) with pizza to enhance their refreshing acidity against rich cheese and sauce. White wines such as Vermentino or Pinot Grigio should be well-chilled (45-50°F) to provide a crisp contrast to hot, greasy toppings. The combination of hot pizza and properly temperature-controlled wine creates an ideal flavor balance that enhances both components.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine pairs best with white sauce pizza versus red sauce pizza?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red sauce pizza's tomato acidity pairs naturally with Italian reds like Chianti or Montepulciano d'Abruzzo, whose bright acidity complements the sauce's natural tartness. White sauce pizzas made with ricotta or alfredo need wines with enough richness to match the creamy base—try Chardonnay, Soave, or even a light Pinot Noir. The key is matching the wine's body and acidity to the sauce's intensity and fat content for optimal harmony.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive wines worth it for pizza night, or should I stick to budget options?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Budget-friendly wines ($10-20) often work excellently with pizza because the dish's bold flavors can overpower subtle nuances in expensive bottles. Italian wines like basic Chianti, Montepulciano d'Abruzzo, or even quality Lambrusco provide authentic pairings without breaking the bank. Save your premium wines for more delicate dishes where you can appreciate their complexity—pizza's robust flavors call for honest, straightforward wines that complement rather than compete.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for pizza?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic for the occasion—big Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo can overwhelm pizza's flavors and create harsh clashes with tomato sauce. Another frequent error is serving red wine too warm, which amplifies alcohol heat against spicy toppings like pepperoni or jalapeños. Focus on medium-bodied wines with good acidity and serve them at proper temperatures for the best pizza pairing experience.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can sparkling wine work with pizza, and if so, which types?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling wines are surprisingly excellent with pizza because their bubbles and acidity cut through cheese and grease while cleansing the palate. Italian Lambrusco pairs beautifully with pepperoni or sausage pizza, while Prosecco complements lighter toppings like margherita or vegetable pizzas. For a fun twist, try rosé Champagne or Cava with prosciutto and arugula pizza—the bubbles enhance the salty-peppery combination perfectly.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do spicy pizza toppings affect wine selection?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Spicy toppings like jalapeños, spicy salami, or hot sauce require wines with lower alcohol and higher residual sugar to cool the heat—try German Riesling, Lambrusco, or even rosé. Avoid high-alcohol reds which amplify spiciness, and instead opt for fruit-forward wines like Beaujolais or Portuguese Vinho Verde. The wine's sweetness and effervescence (if applicable) will provide relief from capsaicin heat while maintaining flavor harmony with the pizza's other elements.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is it better to choose wine based on the pizza sauce or the toppings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Start with the sauce as your base pairing, then adjust for dominant toppings—the sauce covers the entire pizza and provides the foundational flavor profile. For red sauce pizzas, choose wines with complementary acidity, then consider if heavy toppings like sausage require more body, or if vegetables call for lighter styles. When toppings significantly outweigh the sauce (like a meat-heavy pizza), let the protein guide your selection while ensuring the wine still harmonizes with the overall dish.</p>
